'''Folkvid''' was the [[lawspeaker]] of [[Värmland]] during the second half of the 12th century. He was the father of [[Haakon the Crazy|Håkon Galen]], an [[earl]] whose son [[Knut Håkonsson]] was a claimant for the Norwegian throne.<ref>{{cite web
|url=     https://nbl.snl.no/H%C3%A5kon_Galen|title= Håkon Galen|publisher =   Norsk biografisk leksikon |author= Knut Peter Lyche Arstad|accessdate= June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=      https://nbl.snl.no/Knut_H%C3%A5konsson|title= Knut Håkonsson|publisher =   Norsk biografisk leksikon |author= Knut Peter Lyche Arstad|accessdate= June 1, 2017}}</ref>

Folkvid is only known from the ''[[Bagler sagas]]'', where he is mentioned by virtue of his marriage to [[Cecilia Sigurdsdotter]], an illegitimate daughter of Norwegian king [[Sigurd Munn]]. The forced marriage was arranged by the [[earl]] [[Erling Skakke]]. It was annulled in 1184 by  the [[archbishop of Nidaros]], on the initiative of Cecilia's half-brother, king [[Sverre I of Norway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=       https://nbl.snl.no/Cecilia_Sigurdsdatter|title= Cecilia Sigurdsdatter|publisher =   Norsk biografisk leksikon |author= Knut Helle|accessdate= June 1, 2017}}</ref> Most Swedish historians have questioned the historical existence of Folkvid, probably due to lack of reference in Swedish sources from the time.<ref>Jan E  Almquist (1954) ''Lagsagor och domsagor i Sverige''  (Stockholm: Norstedts förlag)</ref>

