'''Jean-Baptiste Perrier''' (or '''Duperrier'''; alias '''Goman''' or '''Gauman''') was an ex-slave leader who led a peasant revolt in Southern [[Grand'Anse (department)|Grand'Anse]], [[Haiti]] between 1807 and 1820.<ref name="Ramsey2011">{{cite book|last=Ramsey|first=Kate|title=The Spirits and the Law: Vodou and Power in Haiti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LShSMaxwImkC&pg=PA282|accessdate=3 July 2011|date=30 April 2011|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-70379-4|pages=282–}}</ref> For a brief period, he essentially ran a separate, independent government from Haiti's central government.

==Early years==
Perrier or Duperrier may have a been a slave on the Perrier plantation in the area of the [[Plaine des Cayes]].<ref name="Théodat2003">{{cite book|last=Théodat|first=Jean-Marie Dulix|title=Haïti république dominicaine: une île pour deux, 1804-1916|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-h36KCEYC3oC&pg=PA148|accessdate=3 July 2011|year=2003|publisher=Katrthala Editions|language=French|isbn=978-2-84586-379-8|pages=148–}}</ref>  In 1792, after a plantation revolt, general [[André Rigaud]] negotiated a settlement with slaves and masters which included 700 [[manumission]]s.  Goman may have been one of the ''[[affranchi]]s''.<ref name="Nicholls1985">{{cite book|last=Nicholls|first=David|title=Haiti in Caribbean context: ethnicity, economy and revolt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2r8XAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=3 July 2011|year=1985|publisher=Macmillan in association with St. Antony's College Oxford|isbn=978-0-333-29083-5|page=171}}</ref>

==Career==
Goman, Nicolas Regnier, and Gilles Bénech were ex-slave leaders of the Platons insurrections of 1792-93. Subsequently, Goman became a company captain in the Third Regiment of the legion, though Goman proved to be a chronic deserter. After the civil war, Goman returned to his former master's plantation, again becoming a [[maroon (people)|maroon]] after the French arrival. He met Jean Panier, and became the leader of his band after Panier's death, joining with Benech and Regnier still later. In 1803, Goman and Regnier had devised a plan of attack against Tiburon, assisted by plantation workers, who had deserted in large numbers, joining the insurrection. They were aided by [[mulatto]] officers of the French army.<ref name="Fick1990">{{cite book|last=Fick|first=Carolyn E.|title=The making of Haïti: the Saint Domingue revolution from below|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7AfPEIPHBCIC&pg=PA225|accessdate=3 July 2011|year=1990|publisher=Univ. of Tennessee Press|isbn=978-0-87049-667-7|pages=225, 230, 233–35–}}</ref>

From 1807 to 1819, Goman led an autonomous farmers' republic that was situated in the southwest.<ref name="Blackburn1988">{{cite book|last=Blackburn|first=Robin|title=The overthrow of colonial slavery, 1776-1848|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JndLInWWjx4C&pg=PA254|accessdate=3 July 2011|year=1988|publisher=Verso|isbn=978-0-86091-901-8|pages=254–}}</ref>
The peasant insurrection was financed by [[Henri Christophe]] and he had kept up a [[Kikongo]] tradition with his group of maroons until 1820.<ref name="Girard2010">{{cite book|last=Girard|first=Philippe|title=Haiti: The Tumultuous History--From Pearl of the Caribbean to Broken Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L5KnihgGoIMC&pg=PA66|accessdate=3 July 2011|date=14 September 2010|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-10661-1|pages=66–}}</ref><ref name="Lefebvre1998">{{cite book|last=Lefebvre|first=Claire|title=Creole genesis and the acquisition of grammar: the case of Haitian creole|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VxP9Q6wg4k0C&pg=PA57|accessdate=2 July 2011|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-59382-3|page=57}}</ref>  At the height of the insurrection, Goman was essentially running a separate independent government from Haiti's central government.<ref name="Mackenzie1830">{{cite book|last=Mackenzie|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Mackenzie (diplomat)|title=Notes on Haiti: made during a residence in that republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7gCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA79|accessdate=3 July 2011|year=1830|publisher=H. Colburn and R. Bentley|pages=79, 81–}}</ref>  Goman was pursued by Gens. Jérôme Maximilien Borgella and Lys for nine months before his ultimate defeat in 1820.<ref name="Ramsey2011" /><ref name="Mackenzie1830" />

