{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}} {{Infobox LGBT rights | location_header = Tajikistan {{flagicon|TJK}} | image = Tajikistan (orthographic projection).svg | caption = [[Tajikistan]] | legal_status = Legal<ref name="ILGA 2012">[http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2012.pdf State-sponsored Homophobia A world survey of laws prohibiting same sex activity between consenting adults] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611181908/http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2012.pdf |date=11 June 2012 }}</ref> | gender_identity_expression = Transgender people can change legal gender following surgery | recognition_of_relationships = No | adoption = No | military = No | discrimination_protections = <!-- ([[#Discrimination protections|see below]]) --> }}
'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT)''' persons in '''Tajikistan''' face legal challenges not experienced by non-[[LGBT]] residents. Both male and female same-sex sexual activity are legal in [[Tajikistan]], but same-sex couples and households headed by same-sex couples are not eligible for the same legal protections available to heterosexual married couples.<ref name="ILGA 2012"/>
LGBT people tend to face frequent discrimination, harassment and violence from the authorities and the Muslim-majority public.<ref name="guardian"/>
==Legality of same-sex sexual activity== Both male and female same-sex sexual activity have been legal in [[Tajikistan]] since 1998.<ref name="ILGA 2012"/> The age of consent is 16, regardless of gender or sexual orientation.<ref>[http://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20071127194808/http://www.interpol.int/Public/Children/SexualAbuse/NationalLaws/CsaTajikistan.pdf National Laws – Legislation of Interpol member states on sexual offences against children – Tajikistan]</ref>
==Recognition of same-sex relationships== Tajikistan does not recognize same-sex unions.
==Gender identity and expression== Transgender people "face a lot of stigma and discrimination" in Tajikistan.<ref name="transgender"/>
Under Tajik law, transgender people may change their legal gender on their passport if they provide a medical statement that they have undergone [[sex reassignment surgery]]. In practice, however, the lack of awareness, coupled with corruption and bureaucracy, means the process can be far more difficult. As of 2014, they have only been two gender change operations in Tajikistan; the first in 2001 and the second in January 2014.<ref name="transgender">[https://iwpr.net/global-voices/transgender-tajikistan Transgender in Tajikistan]</ref>
==Living conditions== Even though the law does not prohibit same-sex sexual activity, the actual situation in the country is not favourable for [[LGBT]] people. This is mostly due to local religion and beliefs, as well as outside influence. Harassment from police and the public is common.<ref name=gaystarnews-tajikistan-homophobia>{{cite web|last=Leach|first=Anna|title=Tajikistan rife with homophobia|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/tajikistan-rife-homophobia|accessdate=24 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sodiqov|first=Alexander|title=Tajikistan Remains ‘Hell for Gays’|url=https://globalvoicesonline.org/2013/01/20/tajikistan-remains-hell-for-gays/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UPR Submission on Sexual Rights in Tajikistan|url=http://www.labrys.kg/files/Labrys__Equal_Opportunities__SRI_-_Joint_Submission_-_TAJIKISTAN_-_Oct._2011.pdf|accessdate=24 February 2014|date=October 2011}}</ref> In 2017, the authorities drew up an "official list" of LGBT citizens following two state operations named "Morality" and "Purge".<ref name="guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/17/tajikistan-gay-lesbian-register-medical-checks|title=Tajikistan authorities draw up list of gay and lesbian citizens|publisher=The Guardian|date=17 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/10/20/theres-a-rising-global-tide-of-crackdowns-on-lgbt-communities/|title=There's a rising global tide of crackdown on LGBT communities|publisher=The Washington Post|date=20 October 2017}}</ref>
