'''The ladder of opportunity''' is a catchphrase coined by former Australian Opposition Leader [[Mark Latham]] to describe the process of social advancement or the elevation to higher social classes of [[Australia]]n citizens. After defeating [[Kim Beazley]] for the role of [[List of Australian Opposition Leaders|Leader of the Opposition]], Mark Latham coined the political slogan in his first press conference to describe what he stood for as [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] leader and alternative [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]].

''The ladder of opportunity'' was a phase to inspire middle class 'aspirational' Australian voters. [[Mark Latham]] recognised that the primary concern of voters was personal [[economic]] advancement, and coined an easy-to-understand phrase to capture the minds of the traditional Labor voter.

The phrase would feature prominently in the [[Australian federal election, 2004|2004 federal election]]; an election that Labor and Latham would go on to lose.

{{DEFAULTSORT:Ladder Of Opportunity}}
